type.name: SecretSyncProperties
type.doc: The properties of the SecretSync instance.

properties.name: secretProviderClassName
properties.doc: SecretProviderClassName specifies the name of the SecretProviderClass resource, which contains the information needed to access the cloud provider secret store.

properties.name: serviceAccountName
properties.doc: ServiceAccountName specifies the name of the service account used to access the cloud provider secret store. The audience field in the service account token must be passed as parameter in the controller configuration. The audience is used when requesting a token from the API server for the service account; the supported audiences are defined by each provider.

properties.name: kubernetesSecretType
properties.doc: Type specifies the type of the Kubernetes secret object, e.g. "Opaque" or"kubernetes.io/tls". The controller must have permission to create secrets of the specified type.

properties.name: forceSynchronization
properties.doc: ForceSynchronization can be used to force the secret synchronization. The secret synchronization is triggered by changing the value in this field. This field is not used to resolve synchronization conflicts.

properties.name: objectSecretMapping
properties.doc: An array of SecretObjectData that maps secret data from the external secret provider to the Kubernetes secret. Each entry specifies the source secret in the external provider and the corresponding key in the Kubernetes secret.

valueType.name: KubernetesSecretObjectMapping
valueType.doc: Properties defining the mapping between a cloud secret store object and a Kubernetes Secret.

properties.name: sourcePath
properties.doc: SourcePath is the identifier for the secret data as defined by the external secret provider. This is the key or path to the secret in the provider's system, which gets mounted to a specific path in the pod. The value should match the name of the secret as specified in the SecretProviderClass's objects array.

properties.name: targetKey
properties.doc: TargetKey is the key in the Kubernetes secret's data field where the secret value will be stored. This key is used to reference the secret data within Kubernetes, and it should be unique within the secret.

properties.name: status
properties.doc: SecretSyncStatus defines the observed state of the secret synchronization process.

type.name: SecretSyncStatus
type.doc: SecretSyncStatus defines the observed state of the secret synchronization process.

properties.name: lastSuccessfulSyncTime
properties.doc: LastSuccessfulSyncTime represents the last time the secret was retrieved from the Provider and updated.

properties.name: conditions
properties.doc: Conditions represent the status of the secret create and update processes. The status can be True, False, or Unknown with various reasons and messages explaining the state. Examples of reasons include CreateSucceeded, ProviderError, InvalidClusterSecretLabelError, InvalidClusterSecretAnnotationError, UnknownError, ValidatingAdmissionPolicyCheckFailed, UserInputValidationFailed, ControllerSpcError, ControllerInternalError, NoValueChange, and ValueChangeOrForceUpdateDetected.

valueType.name: SecretSyncCondition
valueType.doc: A condition represents the status of the secret create and update processes.

properties.name: lastTransitionTime
properties.doc: LastTransitionTime is the last time the condition transitioned from one status to another. This should be when the underlying condition changed. If that is not known, then using the time when the API field changed is acceptable.

properties.name: message
properties.doc: Message is a human readable message indicating details about the transition. This may be an empty string.

properties.name: observedGeneration
properties.doc: ObservedGeneration represents the .metadata.generation that the condition was set based upon. For instance, if .metadata.generation is currently 12, but the .status.conditions[x].observedGeneration is 9, the condition is out of date with respect to the current state of the instance.

properties.name: reason
properties.doc: Reason contains a programmatic identifier indicating the reason for the condition's last transition. Producers of specific condition types may define expected values and meanings for this field, and whether the values are considered a guaranteed API. The value should be a CamelCase string. This field may not be empty.

properties.name: status
properties.doc: Status of the condition, one of True, False, Unknown.

properties.name: type
properties.doc: Type of condition in CamelCase or in foo.example.com/CamelCase. Many .condition.type values are consistent across resources like Available, but because arbitrary conditions can be useful (see .node.status.conditions), the ability to de-conflict is important. The regex it matches is (dns1123SubdomainFmt/)?(qualifiedNameFmt)
